(:kind :chapter :book "Reference Manual" :chapter-number 13 :title "Chapter 13 — The fuel budget" :source-path "git://origin/main/scheme-books/reference/13-the-fuel-budget.md" :size 2865 :sha256 "de8a06304b79e883" :content "---\nslug: sakura-scheme-book-reference-13\ntitle: The fuel budget\nbook: reference\nchapter: 13\nof: 16\npart: II\napp: scheme-repl\npalette: book-standard\ncanonical: true\nowner: docs-team (Lane 6)\nphilosopher-lens: [popper]\nstatus: draft\nlast-reviewed: 2026-07-12\nprev: 12-first-class-continuations\nnext: 14-the-five-gate-dispatcher\n---\n\n# Chapter 13 — The fuel budget\n\nSakura Scheme never runs forever. Every execution carries fuel; each\nstep burns some. When fuel is out, the interpreter stops. That's the\nbounded-execution guarantee that makes it safe to run untrusted\ncarts.\n\n> **Sakura says**\n>\n> Fuel is a promise to the operator. Nothing I run will hang your\n> phone. When a cart runs out of fuel, it halts and I explain.\n\n## The rule\n\n```\nevery primitive call:      1 unit\nevery user-function call:  1 + body cost\nevery allocation:          1 + size / 1024\nevery network call:        expensive; separately budgeted\nevery timer wait:          NOT counted (waits are free)\n```\n\n## In practice\n\n```sakura-scheme\n(with-fuel 1000\n  (map square '(1 2 3 4 5)))     ; costs ~15 units, well under budget\n;=> (1 4 9 16 25)\n\n(with-fuel 100\n  (let loop ()\n    (loop)))                      ; runs out of fuel; halts\n;=> #<error :fuel-exhausted :consumed 100>\n```\n\nEvery cart gets a default fuel budget appropriate to its tier. A\nwhite-tier cart has less fuel than a magic-tier one. See the color-\ntier canon in the curator conventions.\n\n## The five-gate dispatcher (preview)\n\nChapter 14 covers this in depth. Preview: the dispatcher gates\nverbs by tier + capability + registration + fuel + gate.\n\n- **Tier gate** — is the caller in a tier that allows this verb?\n- **Capability gate** — is the verb available on this surface?\n- **Registration gate** — is the verb actually registered?\n- **Fuel gate** — is enough fuel left to run it?\n- **Custom gate** — verb-specific gate (auth, quotas, etc.)\n\nIf any gate refuses, dispatch returns a legible error.\n\n## Sakura reads her own fuel\n\n```sakura-scheme\n(define (careful-work)\n  (let loop ((remaining (fuel-remaining)))\n    (when (> remaining 100)\n      (do-one-step)\n      (loop (fuel-remaining)))\n    (when (<= remaining 100)\n      (checkpoint)\n      (report-out-of-fuel))))\n```\n\nShe can query her own fuel and act on it — stop cleanly, save state,\nreport out. This is the ANTI-DOS discipline in code.\n\n## Why this matters\n\n- **Nothing runs forever.** The classic infinite-fixed-point trap\n  from Book of Words ch 17 halts safely.\n- **Nothing eats your phone's battery.** Bounded execution means\n  bounded compute.\n- **Failures are legible.** `:fuel-exhausted` beats a mysterious\n  hang.\n\n## Cross-links\n\n- [[book-of-reference]] ch 14 — the five-gate dispatcher.\n- [[book-of-words]] ch 17 — paradoxes (why we bound execution).\n- [[book-of-don-ts]] — refusal register (fuel refusal shape).\n\n---\n\nTurn the page.\n")
